      "date": "2019-06-08 03:18:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nYeah, as I hope is clear from the text here and in the i/o 500 tracker ticket, this is not a proposal for something to do permanently, just something quick for testing.  (Though I am considering arguing for disabling strided readahead, unless we can fix it. ;) )",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2226dff4db7a8342c8168606ab560728f578c9c2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-06-08 03:32:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(3 comments)\n\nOof.  Since I spent all of yesterday on this... ;)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "1f7c68d605b230390901ba28973ebe8a67077425",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-06-08 03:33:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nNote that there is also some sort of off by one error when transitioning from sequential to strided mode, where we start the readahead for the strided block one page too late.  (It is not that we miss the first page, then start readahead - We do readahead before we try to read that first page, we just start one page too late.  Again, look at the misses in debug logs.)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "0402b76821299a9af4ed871ef71b23bcc7618987",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-06-08 03:38:50.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nAfter looking at all of this, in particular the ria_end and RPC size stuff...\n\nI didn't look very closely at the ria_end stuff, perhaps there is an easy fix or perhaps it is not the root of the small RPCs problem.  But assuming the ria_end modification is needed to get good RPC sizes, then I don't see how that can work with strided readahead as currently implemented.\n\nAnd we have to have:\nA low miss rate\nThe largest possible RPCs (at least the same size as the userspace i/os, no smaller except when split between stripes)\n\nIdeally, we also want a low discard rate, so we're not wasting many pages, but that's less important.\n\nNote that the existing readahead tests in sanity don't catch any of this because they look almost entirely at discards.  If readahead were off entirely, they would pass because discards would be 0.  Similarly, if readahead is missing a page on every read, it's not much use.  But it won't have any discards.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "52966768019a32cef0152f96f90e6d921e10341e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 428,
        "name": "Wang Shilong",
        "email": "wangshilong1991@gmail.com",
        "username": "wangshilong",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-06-10 09:44:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nPatrick,\n\nCurrent Stride RA detection is based on Page index, so if Stride Read is not aligned on page, it will definitely break Current detection.\n\nI am trying to rewrite Stride Readahead based on bytes offset, so that we will support\nun-aligned page Stride read without problems.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2ac3bc41373bd4c516e9dfabcf2db982e19b2e3c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-06-10 15:23:10.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nYeah, definitely the current readahead can't correctly understand unaligned i/o, but I should stress:\n\nIt also can't do aligned i/o right now.  My description of the problems in my previous comment is from a test of 1 MiB strided i/o with a stride of 1 MiB - IE, reading every other MiB.  This is about the simplest case possible and strided readahead fails badly.  Obviously the i/o 500 unlaigned case is even worse. ;)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "1fb1e7fbc5aa31befd9b53471e85b87b98ab0ab3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-06-10 15:23:36.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nNow for longer thoughts...\n\nGood!  Personally, I think for stride detection we should use the i/o, ie, the offset and count that come in from VFS, rather than try to figure out by checking every page of an i/o.  I also wonder if we should observe and store this stride info from the i/o separately.  A problem with the current readahead is that this info is sort of ... embedded in the readahead state, and inferred from that state.\n\nThis leads to the problem where tweaking the readahead window to be RPC aligned breaks strided readahead, because the state is all jammed in to one place.\n\nIt's true that moving the stride detection up to the i/o layer means we couldn't do strided readahead for mmap, but I don't think that's a big case and I think it's worth it for the simplification it allows.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ae49c2e8c098ad4090f0a895b26e5e02ec1777df",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-06-10 15:26:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nBTW, I am thinking about (and slowly working on) some improved tests for readahead, because our current ones only worry about discards.  This means that they don't notice when we miss on literally every single read - They only notice if we read ahead pages we don't use.  (Which is less serious than missing a page we needed...)\n\nObviously we should check for both, but misses are a fatal flaw, (continuous misses rendering readahead useless), discards are an annoyance...",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "175a729f49d18d8fde993022fa22b11939bd7e86",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-08-16 19:53:06.000000000",
      "message": "Abandoned\n\nShilong is fixing strided readahead under LU-12644.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    }
  ],
